erive from the Old English personal name <i>Uffa</i> + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’. For the Huntingdonshire placename see   Offord  , with which the surname may have been confused."],"variants":[{"name":"Offord","meanings":["English (East Anglia and London): habitational name from Offord Cluny and Offord Darcy in Huntindgonshire. The placename derives from Old English <i>upp</i> ‘up, upper’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","English: alternatively, from a lost place called Offord near Pennyford in Wootton Wawen, Warwickshire. The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Offa</i> + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’."]}]},{"name":"Ela","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently an altered form of <b>Hilda</b> , not in use before the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":20,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ela Ufford was born in 1362, in Belstead, Suffolk, England, her father, Edmund Ufford, was 26 and her mother, Sibyl Pierrepoint, was 22. She married Sir Miles Stapleton III about 1375, in Bedale, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died on 10 April 1418, in Bedale, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 56, and was buried in Ingham, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"1362–10 April 1418":"1362–10. aprill 1418","1362–1418":"1362–1418","1353–1419":"1353–1419","1375–1417":"1375–1417","1379–1438":"1379–1438","1383–1456":"1383–1456","1336–1374":"1336–1374","1340–1375":"1340–1375","1374":"1374